# 🔧 Industrial Valve Position Control using STM32 (Button + Servo + OLED)

## 📌 Overview

This project implements a **valve position control system** using a push button, servo motor, and OLED display. The system allows the user to cycle through predefined valve positions (LEFT, CENTER, RIGHT) using a single button, while the OLED provides real-time visual feedback of the selected state.

---

## 🎯 Features

* Button-based mode selection
* Servo motor position control (0°, 90°, 180°)
* OLED-based user interface
* Debounced input handling
* Real-time embedded control

---

## 🧠 Working Principle

A push button connected to a GPIO pin is used to cycle through three modes. Each mode corresponds to a specific servo position:

* LEFT → 0°
* CENTER → 90°
* RIGHT → 180°

The selected mode is displayed on the OLED with a cursor (`>`), and the servo motor moves accordingly using PWM signals.

---

## 🔧 Hardware Used

* STM32 (e.g., STM32F446RE / Nucleo board)
* Servo Motor
* SSD1306 OLED Display (I2C)
* Push Button

---

## 🔌 Pin Configuration

| Peripheral | Pin                  |
| ---------- | -------------------- |
| Button     | PA6                  |
| Servo PWM  | TIM3 CH2 (e.g., PC7) |
| I2C SCL    | PB8                  |
| I2C SDA    | PB9                  |

---

## ⚙️ Software Configuration

* IDE: STM32CubeIDE
* Language: C (HAL Drivers)
* Timer: PWM Mode (Servo control)
* I2C: 100 kHz
* GPIO: Input (Pull-up)

---

## 📺 OLED Display

Example UI:

```id="z9v4f1"
> LEFT
  CENTER
  RIGHT
```

* `>` indicates selected mode
* Display updates only when selection changes

---

## 🔄 System Flow

```id="d1n6zs"
Button Press → Mode Change → OLED Update → Servo Movement
```

---

## ▶️ How to Run

1. Open project in STM32CubeIDE
2. Build and flash the code
3. Press button to cycle through modes
4. Observe servo movement and OLED updates

---

## ⚠️ Notes

* Ensure servo is powered properly (external 5V recommended)
* Button should be configured with pull-up resistor
* OLED I2C address typically `0x3C`

---

